<p><em>Fire Elves problems:</em></p>
<p><strong>FIRE ELVES ARE ACTIVELY CREATING NEW PROBLEMS</strong></p>
<p><strong>Economic Action</strong>:&nbsp;</p>
<p>Infrastructure (Establishment): Goldrush [the Fury, Barrabus, and the CPC]</p>
<p><em>Action: Create village &lsquo;Disr&rsquo; on the gold deposit three squares WNW of Surt</em></p>
<p>The Fury is a little&hellip; concerned about the Hunger&rsquo;s recent absences. The disappearances in the previous months have mostly been understandable (and explained away as time off for a thoroughly overworked bureaucrat who doesn&rsquo;t know how to stop). However, as of late last winter, the Hunger has been absent from more meetings and events than he&rsquo;s been present for, and at this point he hasn&rsquo;t been seen in public in weeks.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Something must be going on.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Unfortunately, with the war to the south still ongoing, and issues within Surt still as complicated as ever, the Fury doesn&rsquo;t really have time to investigate for herself. And the CPC, lacking a Hunger to officiate, is looking for Triumvirate members to stand as official support for &ldquo;Project Disr,&rdquo; the plan to claim the (ostensibly) mineral rich mountains to the west north west.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Fury is happy to provide official support, but has little time for most of the important planning and layout activities -- she&rsquo;s still locked up in overall coordination, civil defense planning, and of course another round of scanning rituals beneath Surt itself. She drags Barrabus into the mix, letting him and the Phoenix Imperialis sign off on CPC plans while she worries about the rest of the nation.</p>
<p>The Council of Firebirds is unaware of the true bounty Disr would rest on, but is still generally eager to help, as this helps cement their political position, provides another settlement that will generally support them, and gives plenty of room for prospecting opportunities of their own. Barry keeps an eye on them, but stays mostly out of the actual civil planning work (apart from making certain there is room enough for walls, and adding a few artistic flourishes where appropriate).&nbsp;</p>
<p>He is more concerned about the Hunger&rsquo;s absence -- and is, in fact, about to investigate, when a strange commotion interrupts the afternoon Council meeting&hellip;</p>
<p><a href="https://dev71687.service-now.com/nav_to.do?uri=x_339494_mdalpha_rolls.do?sys_id=020c3ed2db000010e7a0a08a48961949">Result</a>: 3 advantage, 1 success</p>
<p>But before that commotion occurs, there&rsquo;s a new problem. The terrain leading up to Disr is exceptionally treacherous, and supporting the work crews moving up to Disr&rsquo; site becomes increasingly difficult as time goes on. In an effort to push construction forward, Barrabus coordinates &ldquo;supply runs&rdquo; from Surt&rsquo;s prolific gardeners (adding the <strong>Verdant Rooftop Gardens</strong> bonus die to this check, as the food is passed to Disr&rsquo;s work crews and new settlers), and pushes to make extensive use of the CPC&rsquo;s roadplanning skills to make Disr as connected to Surt as possible (invoking <strong>All Roads lead to Surt / Fortified Roadways</strong>).</p>
<p>Reroll: 5 advantage, 1 success</p>
<p><strong>Political Action</strong>:&nbsp;</p>
<p>Spycraft (Cloak and Dagger): Almost Got &lsquo;Em [Ashwalker Tsun]</p>
<p>Tsun has spent a number of months recovering and resolidifying her base (after some slight embarrassment not very long ago). And during the last season&rsquo;s campaign, her soldiers -- now more unified and organized than ever -- almost managed to catch what Tsun is certain was a Wolf Elf in action.</p>
<p>But almost isn&rsquo;t good enough. Tsun needs a win, and it's high time she got personally involved again, to make sure it happens.</p>
<p><a href="https://dev71687.service-now.com/nav_to.do?uri=x_339494_mdalpha_rolls.do?sys_id=372543d6db000010e7a0a08a48961904">Result</a>: 1 success</p>
<p><strong>Military Action:</strong></p>
<p>Conventional Warfare (Defensive Ops): Operation Acme [The Terror and Barrabus Leafstorm]</p>
<p> <em>Includes upgrade from Fire for Effect (1 economy dmg)</em></p>
<p><em> </em><em>Includes Hot Gates (advantage converted to enemy disadvantage)</em></p>
<p><em> </em><em>Includes upgrade from Concealed Positions (Fall Year 3)</em></p>
<p><em>Includes upgrade from Trapped Approach (Riverhaven)</em></p>
<p>Acme (&alpha;&kappa;&mu;Î®). Aboleth, noun, meaning &lsquo;peak&rsquo; or &lsquo;zenith&rsquo;. &ldquo;Coyotes&rsquo; bane&rdquo; in some old folklore. The Terror intends to put that to the test.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Final preparations for the Battle of Riverhaven:</p>
<p>Pre-battle:&nbsp;</p>
<ol>
<li>Harassment methods (Dreamdust traps, camouflaged raiders and emplacements, and disruption of known resting points along the path to Riverhaven) will be used to weaken approaching forces</li>
<li>Maybe it's just nerves, or memories of how close her last several battles have ended. Maybe its renewed hope, or superstition, or lip service to something that was once her life. <br />Regardless of the source, the Terror is compelled to give service to Calestros before the battle, as she did when she was young, before fire burned it all away. A few days before the battle, she pulls an old vial of ink from her pack, and walks out into the desert to commune. Ink smeared on her face and arms, staring up at the stars, and maintaining a backwards yoga position that keeps her head upside-down, until her eyes fill with streaks "like Calestros' many arms embracing the world"</li>
</ol>
<p>Terror&rsquo;s vision blurs slightly. She can see something. The streaks of ink in her vision shift. They begin to move. Terror can see arms reaching for her. They are not grasping or clawing, but instead reaching out for an embrace.</p>
<p><em>And I never stopped.</em></p>
<p>The vision fades.</p>
<p>in-battle:</p>
<p>Cazadores are known priority targets for Coyzadore units. To take advantage of that:</p>
<ol>
<li> Cazadores unit 1 will stand in formation in front of the Elect. Thanks to coordination between Breaker and Terror, Cazadores 1 will wait for inevitable charge from Coyzadores units, and then pull back behind the Elect (as an immediate action), allowing the Elect to accept the Coyzadores charge (also as an immediate action). Other units can then move in and attempt to finish off the Coyzadores.</li>
<li> Cazadores unit 2 will stand in formation adjacent to the Chevaliers unit, which will provide its teamwork bonus to Cazadores 2, allowing the Chevaliers to intercept charges aimed for them. At the Coyzadores' charge, the Chevaliers will accept the charge in place of them, and engage the Coyzadores long enough for additional units to move in and lock the Coyzadores.</li>
</ol>
<p>Cazadore units can then move to engage enemy heavy infantry units, in an attempt to remove them from the field. Heavy infantry will focus on removing the Coyzadores before they can respond, and will then attempt to push enemy light infantry from the field. Archers and other ranged units will focus on disrupting light infantry first, as they're likely to break early.</p>
<p><a href="https://dev71687.service-now.com/nav_to.do?uri=x_339494_mdalpha_rolls.do?sys_id=11cd3405db000010e7a0a08a489619f8%26sysparm_view=Player">Results</a>: 2 advantage, 2 successes, 1 triumph</p>
<p><strong>Mental Action:</strong></p>
<p>Academics (Magic): Ritual Homicide [the Fury] (Deep Scan)</p>
<p> <em>Includes bonus die from Winter Year 3</em></p>
<p>The Fury is irritated. And maybe a little stressed out. But that doesn&rsquo;t mean she&rsquo;s going to give up. She just needs to pour more effort into it. And maybe, just maybe, play a little smarter.</p>
<p>So trying to read through the ley lines isn&rsquo;t working. But what about &ldquo;from&rdquo; the ley lines? They should be directly impacted by the sizeable groundswell of energy beneath them. Maybe the trick to understanding the Marr is to read the magic flowing through it, and try to determine what that says about the physical world. Study the auric movement to determine how deep the magma pocket beneath goes, and maybe what its made of.</p>
<p><a href="https://dev71687.service-now.com/nav_to.do?uri=x_339494_mdalpha_rolls.do?sys_id=61e08b56db000010e7a0a08a4896196f">Results</a>: 1 advantage</p>
<p>Okay, that didn&rsquo;t help in the slightest. Clearly working smarter is not the Fury&rsquo;s forte. ...Or maybe she just doesn&rsquo;t have enough at stake.</p>
<p>Fury concentrates on her own part in this. If this lava vent goes up, all of their work in Surt will have been for naught. All of the people who survived Muspelham will be dead. All of the work they put into building a future for themselves will be gone. And history will remember the elves of Muspelham as&hellip; slaves. Slaves and victims, lost but ultimately meaningless in the endless swell of history.</p>
<p>All she&rsquo;ll ever have been is a foolish girl, enslaved to a tyrant.</p>
<p><strong>Fury invokes her High Concept, and spends 1 fate point to reroll this check.</strong></p>
<p>Reroll: 2 successes, 1 Triumph</p>
<p>...Fury has learned &ldquo;work angrier, not smarter.&rdquo;</p>
<p><strong>Hunger Action:</strong></p>
<p>Research!</p>
<p>What the Hunger knows:</p>
<ol>
<li> This is a divine curse, and the only known counters involve divine cures. Thus, the only cure must involve accepting a divine power or its equivalent. So which divine source are we touching here?</li>
<li> The fact that the Tourist hasn't killed him even when he's outside of Surt suggests that either the Tourist is 100% unaware that he could be infected (which is a little suspicious), or secondary exposure came from another source. He knows he's been down this path before; this is just... suspicious.</li>
<li> All of the evidence seems to suggest that the Dog is now effectively a part of him -- thus, whatever this particular ritual is trying to do must specifically involve changing one's self. So what is it attempting to transform him to? Something that cannot effectively be a Lycanthrope... such as an Outsider?</li>
<li> The change effect itself can be dispelled, but not permanently. That implies that the change itself is a Transformation effect, but that its inherent to the body at this point.</li>
<li> For all this talk about "being part of the core", there's a whole lot of "replacing the existing personality with a new one" going on here. I understand it is supposed to mimic the worst traits of the old one... but it seems more like the typical "just like the old one, but BETTERER" mantra popular with Bellaphex and her assorted worshippers. Which fits, as its a Bellaphexian curse, but the implication of a "cure that would resolve a divine curse that replaces the old personality with a new personality with Bellaphexian traits" suggests that the cure would either have to (a) function just like the better known divine cures, and are thus unreliable, or (b) replace the personality of the subject with a new personality that amplifies non-Bellaphexian traits. And that doesn't fit my old mentor, unless her goal is to push me towards a non-Bellaphexian version that still fits her definition of "gets things done". So, possibility to consider: "cure" is in fact a method to slap infernal or other outsider influence over my core personality so that it no longer qualifies for Lycanthropy, and revokes the Bellaphexian personality change to replace it with an infernal personality change.</li>
</ol>
<p>Craft: Alchemy (to identify the ritual, based on the assumptions above): 36</p>
<p><strong>End of Turn </strong></p>
<h3>Spring Year 3 Results</h3>
<p><strong>Economic- </strong>Congratulations! The settlement of Disr has successfully been founded! It has the following stats:</p>
